    <a title="Starling" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2446676-starling"><img alt="Starling" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1311979749p2/2446676.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/99449286?book_show_action=true">Apr 21, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Starling" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Starling" href="/user/show/2446676-starling">Starling</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2446676-starling?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2446676-starling?shelf=mystery">mystery</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer99449286" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17870619294919046156">I am reading backwards from the most recent book in this series. As I expected the arc about the Watchman begins in this book, and another multi-book arc is also explained in the book.<br/><br/>The main story is about a serial killer who is leaving ticking clocks at his kills. He is killing in ways where the person dies a long and painful death while listening to the clock ticking his life down. He is accompanied by a man who enjoys raping the female victims.<br/><br/>Lincoln Rhyme is brought in to help deal with t</span>
  <span id="freeText17870619294919046156" style="display:none">I am reading backwards from the most recent book in this series. As I expected the arc about the Watchman begins in this book, and another multi-book arc is also explained in the book.<br /><br />The main story is about a serial killer who is leaving ticking clocks at his kills. He is killing in ways where the person dies a long and painful death while listening to the clock ticking his life down. He is accompanied by a man who enjoys raping the female victims.<br /><br />Lincoln Rhyme is brought in to help deal with this pair, but his cop partner/lover Amelia Sachs has been given her own case for the first time, so she is working both cases and can't give full attention to the serial murder. As a result some of the other regulars, including the rookie Pulaski get more work than they usually would.<br /><br />I'm not going to spoil the plot, but there are some interesting twists and turns and an ending that involves some real plot twists that were a real surprise, not just to the reader but also to the characters searching for the killers. Unlike most "plot twists" where the ending is not what you expected, or what would be reasonable, this one is not a cheat and I enjoyed it as I generally wouldn't enjoy the usual "surprise" ending.<br /><br />I'll be looking for more by this author, both going forward and going back.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17870619294919046156" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


