    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2852092312" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2852092312" />
    <a title="Thomas" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/63824806-thomas"><img alt="Thomas" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1484326813p2/63824806.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2852092312?book_show_action=true">Oct 20, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Thomas" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Thomas" href="/user/show/63824806-thomas">Thomas</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780340960639" href="/book/show/6859273-the-cold-moon">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2852092312" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9248433604220011415">After my somewhat disappointing experience with book 6 of this series, I was hoping book 7 would throw me straight into a Jeffery Deaver masterpiece. I have to say I was not overly impressed with The Cold Moon, fortunately this time however, there were some key redeeming features which improved my opinion of the novel somewhat.<br/><br/>This time round, Lincoln Rhyme and his team must solve a number of cases connected by a killer they have labelled The Watchmaker, while Amelia Sachs investigates a couple </span>
  <span id="freeText9248433604220011415" style="display:none">After my somewhat disappointing experience with book 6 of this series, I was hoping book 7 would throw me straight into a Jeffery Deaver masterpiece. I have to say I was not overly impressed with The Cold Moon, fortunately this time however, there were some key redeeming features which improved my opinion of the novel somewhat.<br /><br />This time round, Lincoln Rhyme and his team must solve a number of cases connected by a killer they have labelled The Watchmaker, while Amelia Sachs investigates a couple of deaths within the police force itself which threaten her relationship with Rhyme and the rest of her team.<br /><br />In terms of plot and complexity, I think Deaver really overdid it this time. The story was far too complicated for one novel in my opinion with so many different arcs that really needed more explanation to solve in an effective and tidy way, as he did in the first 5 novels. Unfortunately, I judged book 7 to be somewhat a mess and the fact the ending once again was left quite unresolved irritated me. I hope this does not continue in future novels because otherwise I may have to cease reading Deaver’s work.<br /><br />The major redeeming fact about book 7 was the introduction of one the best characters I have encountered in crime and thriller novels for a long time. The wonderful Kathryn Dance, a kinesics expert whose skills Rhyme finds become invaluable throughout the case. I was also pleased the Deaver managed to introduce us to a new strong female protagonist besides Amelia Sachs, who still remains my favourite red headed policewoman.<br /><br />Not the best of the Lincoln Rhyme books by a long way, but an improvement on book 6. I think The Cold Moon deserves 3.5 stars rounded down. I am still quite attached to Lincoln Rhyme and his team, so I will read a couple more novels before I decide whether to cease reading them. I will definitely be purchasing the first Kathryn Dance novel however because I enjoyed her character so much.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9248433604220011415" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

